242
00:15:12,265 --> 00:15:15,815
The Egyptian spatial configurations can thus be resumed in four simple types:

243
00:15:16,748 --> 00:15:19,558
A = A united Egypt, a strong and conquering State

244
00:15:19,875 --> 00:15:24,015
B = A divided Egypt, but only divided into two States, capable of resisting 

245
00:15:24,015 --> 00:15:26,135
external pressures for at least a certain time

246
00:15:26,533 --> 00:15:30,883
C = A reunited Egypt, but weakened and submitted to external pressures

247
00:15:31,746 --> 00:15:36,236
D = A politically fragmented Egypt dominated from outside.

248
00:15:38,299 --> 00:15:42,749
However over time, these configurations could be observed 

249
00:15:42,749 --> 00:15:49,109
to progress several times in this order: D => B => A => B, or C => D

250
00:15:49,109 --> 00:15:51,789
This progression corresponded to what we call, in Egyptian history, 

251
00:15:51,789 --> 00:15:55,589
an “empire” (B=>A=>C), framed by intermediate periods (D).

252
00:15:55,589 --> 00:15:57,982
We could thus summarise this into a model of Egyptian history,

253
00:15:58,212 --> 00:16:01,752
which progressed in a complex but recurrent manner, 

254
00:16:01,752 --> 00:16:04,852
according to the Constantinople principle:

255
00:16:04,852 --> 00:16:07,922
The first rectangle represents the Ancient Egyptian Empire 2700-2200 BC.

256
