261
00:16:23,447 --> 00:16:27,057
These repeatable progressions can thus create spatio-temporal scenarios, 

262
00:16:27,057 --> 00:16:30,287
or in other words geo-historical evolutions. 

263
00:16:30,287 --> 00:16:34,287
Their recurrence in different circumstances shows that

264
00:16:34,287 --> 00:16:36,297
space is an essential actor in history. 

265
00:16:36,301 --> 00:16:39,361
Clearly this must not be viewed as deterministic, 

266
00:16:39,495 --> 00:16:43,495
but only as a way of showing that spatial configuration is one of the elements

267
00:16:43,495 --> 00:16:46,375
which comes into play when some decision is made,  

268
00:16:46,375 --> 00:16:50,655
for example in the choice of a capital.
 

269
00:16:50,655 --> 00:16:54,965
It is this sometimes important role of spatial positioning which explains 

270
00:16:54,965 --> 00:16:58,025
the regularity in certain spatio-temporal combinations over history’s long duration.

271
00:16:59,690 --> 00:17:02,640
In conclusion, let us summarise several lessons:

272
00:17:02,640 --> 00:17:05,910
1. Certain spatial configurations, such as the city and the State, 

273
00:17:05,910 --> 00:17:07,610
can be historicised. 

274
00:17:08,292 --> 00:17:12,642
They are not unsurpassable and invariable frameworks of humanity,

275
00:17:12,752 --> 00:17:16,752
but spatial sequences, in these cases territorialised,

276
00:17:16,752 --> 00:17:18,682
limited in time, generally since the end of the Middle Ages up 

277
00:17:18,727 --> 00:17:22,207
until the 20th century. 

278
00:17:22,598 --> 00:17:26,598
Such an intellectual deconstruction should allow us to accept the changes 

279
00:17:26,598 --> 00:17:30,598
in these Modern but inherited political frameworks,

280
00:17:30,598 --> 00:17:33,758
and to accept them not as a tragedy,

281
00:17:33,758 --> 00:17:35,248
but as an inherent consequence of the human condition.

282
00:17:36,107 --> 00:17:40,287
2. The past does not exist as such,

283
00:17:40,287 --> 00:17:44,777
but is always made known to the present through a process of transmission

284
00:17:44,777 --> 00:17:49,197
which necessarily causes its transformation, re-actualisation, and reinvention. 

285
00:17:49,197 --> 00:17:51,347

286
00:17:51,677 --> 00:17:53,277
For example, it would be better to think of development projects,

287
00:17:53,277 --> 00:17:55,517
not as lasting but as transformable.

288
00:17:55,987 --> 00:17:59,647
Whatever money, energy, and power 

289
00:17:59,647 --> 00:18:03,127
is put into a development project, it will only be temporary 

290
00:18:03,127 --> 00:18:06,917
since the social forces which created it won’t exist eternally, 

291
00:18:06,917 --> 00:18:10,917
and the project will last only if it is re-appropriated and transformed. 

292
00:18:11,858 --> 00:18:15,858
It would thus be better to assume the obsolescence of spatial amenities 

293
00:18:15,858 --> 00:18:19,028
and encourage their capacity for re-appropriation rather than to seek 

294
00:18:19,028 --> 00:18:20,918
to lengthen their lifespan.

295
00:18:21,451 --> 00:18:25,451
3. Modes of articulation between space-times 

296
00:18:25,451 --> 00:18:29,171
allow for a better understanding of social dynamics

297
00:18:29,171 --> 00:18:33,171
than when only one spatial or temporal dimension of society is considered. 

298
00:18:33,171 --> 00:18:36,301
This can occur either by synchrony,

299
00:18:36,301 --> 00:18:40,111
that is a social community conceived of as a special structure 

300
00:18:40,111 --> 00:18:42,741
for the appropriation of a space-time, or by diachrony,

301
00:18:42,741 --> 00:18:46,461
in spatio-temporal recurrences and connections.
